1
00:00:01,820 --> 00:00:27,574
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:28,211 --> 00:00:32,338
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed and noble self-awakened one.

3
00:00:34,039 --> 00:00:40,347
So I just say this is our inaugural Full Moon Day meeting.

4
00:00:41,409 --> 00:00:45,375
I've always wanted to do this, but I've never found a way to do it.

5
00:00:45,735 --> 00:00:53,526
So I was really happy when Magda suggested that I try it on this medium.

6
00:00:53,665 --> 00:00:56,429
So I think we can keep this going.

7
00:00:56,781 --> 00:01:06,956
luckily it's fallen on a Sunday and I'm inclined to in the future choose the closest Sunday to the full moon because that's most convenient for people.

8
00:01:07,778 --> 00:01:16,069
In Sri Lanka they are public holidays, all the moons are public holidays so there's no problem in keeping the full moon itself there.

9
00:01:17,712 --> 00:01:24,882
So my idea is that with every full moon we look at some of the teachings of the Buddha

10
00:01:25,198 --> 00:01:29,385
And eventually throughout the year, we cover it all.

11
00:01:29,405 --> 00:01:39,858
So I'm going to start with this lovely little trilogy, a virtuous circle of gratitude, generosity, and renunciation.

12
00:01:40,939 --> 00:01:43,804
So starting with renunciation.

13
00:01:46,628 --> 00:01:47,950
So the big...

14
00:01:48,959 --> 00:02:15,473
problem here that can arise is confusing what it is that we're actually renouncing so remember the body is not our fault when the body has appetite then it has appetite and when you put something uh lovely sweet on the on the tongue it will taste lovely and sweet that's never the problem as you know the problem is our relationship to it which is wanting more

15
00:02:15,841 --> 00:02:21,225
depending on it in order to establish a beautiful mental state.

16
00:02:21,947 --> 00:02:24,569
Now, that's what we've really got to grasp.

17
00:02:25,069 --> 00:02:36,540
We use the sense bases, not because they are just lovely in themselves, but because they are a way of creating a lovely mental state.

18
00:02:37,301 --> 00:02:42,287
Hence, you might have a piece of toast in the evening just to raise your spirits.

19
00:02:42,858 --> 00:02:46,300
Now, the unfortunate thing of that, of course, is that you have dependency.

20
00:02:47,222 --> 00:02:49,503
And that dependency is what we call attachment.

21
00:02:50,365 --> 00:02:52,706
And so there's a suffering there.

22
00:02:52,727 --> 00:02:56,430
See, if there's no bread and there's no toast, well, it's misery, isn't it?

23
00:02:57,211 --> 00:03:06,899
So when we click onto that, we become much more sensitive to this draw towards what is pleasurable.

24
00:03:06,938 --> 00:03:12,003
And this renunciation...

25
00:03:12,135 --> 00:03:17,300
is therefore is not to be confused with, well, the word they use is self-mortification.

26
00:03:17,320 --> 00:03:21,824
In other words, blaming the body for our mental states.

27
00:03:22,945 --> 00:03:25,449
So that's an important distinction to make.

28
00:03:26,870 --> 00:03:31,213
We're not trying to get rid of the pleasures and joys of life at all.

29
00:03:31,775 --> 00:03:34,537
And the Buddha himself did enjoy life.

30
00:03:34,578 --> 00:03:38,100
He enjoyed taste, but he didn't greed for it.

31
00:03:38,341 --> 00:03:40,302
That's what it says in the scriptures.

32
00:03:45,852 --> 00:03:59,806
And this whole idea of renunciation will arise on two different types of grasping, which is one about our wealth and the other about our time.

33
00:04:00,668 --> 00:04:05,453
So we can be greedy with our time, but not greedy with our wealth.

34
00:04:05,913 --> 00:04:10,998
So we can be generous with our wealth, but if somebody asks us to do something for them, we shy off it.

35
00:04:11,637 --> 00:04:13,058
and the other way around.

36
00:04:13,079 --> 00:04:19,827
We can be very happy giving time, but if somebody asks us for a bit of money, we're not inclined to give.

37
00:04:20,728 --> 00:04:23,452
So again, we have to look at that.

38
00:04:23,973 --> 00:04:33,747
And this trilogy, this little virtuous circle of gratitude, generosity, and renunciation, it's not actually

39
00:04:34,233 --> 00:04:39,180
taught in the scriptures themselves as a way to liberation.

40
00:04:39,199 --> 00:04:42,064
This is more a commentary pointed out.

41
00:04:42,985 --> 00:04:46,649
And this, of course, of course, directly with our daily life.

42
00:04:47,029 --> 00:04:51,175
This is our daily life in our daily work in the way we are with people.

43
00:04:51,877 --> 00:05:00,567
So if we can generate that virtuous circle, it's actually drawing us towards liberation.

44
00:05:00,588 --> 00:05:02,451
So letting go of attachment and

45
00:05:02,767 --> 00:05:07,035
Letting go of dependency is the path to liberation.

46
00:05:07,254 --> 00:05:11,963
So you might say that the whole of the path is one of renunciation.

47
00:05:12,624 --> 00:05:15,649
Because eventually you've got to renounce the sense of self.

48
00:05:16,550 --> 00:05:17,891
That's the last thing to go.

49
00:05:17,932 --> 00:05:30,091
This little idea that somewhere within us, we actually do believe ourselves to be this psychophysical organism, for want of a better word.

50
00:05:31,067 --> 00:05:33,211
So that's this renunciation business.

51
00:05:33,632 --> 00:05:39,480
Now, just to go to the front of the trilogy, this sense of gratitude.

52
00:05:39,860 --> 00:05:45,889
Now, as you know, when you feel gratitude, it really is a heartwarming feeling, you know?

53
00:05:45,930 --> 00:05:51,317
And when we feel this gratitude, we always want to repay it.

54
00:05:52,259 --> 00:05:59,910
Now, if we spend some time just considering what we've received,

55
00:06:00,262 --> 00:06:01,202
from our parents.

56
00:06:01,444 --> 00:06:05,709
Our parents gave us our life, you know, our mothers.

57
00:06:06,451 --> 00:06:12,139
When you think about that, you might have problems with your mother and your father.

58
00:06:12,199 --> 00:06:19,608
In fact, somebody once asked, how do you know when you're fully liberated?

59
00:06:20,149 --> 00:06:22,333
And they said, well, go and spend a week with your mother.

60
00:06:24,055 --> 00:06:24,836
And then you'll know.

61
00:06:25,257 --> 00:06:26,538
So...

62
00:06:27,699 --> 00:06:36,971
So it may be that our general relationship is a bit fractious and so on and so forth, but you still have your life through your parents.

63
00:06:38,093 --> 00:06:43,879
And the Buddha said that even if you were to carry them on your shoulders the whole of your life, you'd never repay them.

64
00:06:44,360 --> 00:06:46,202
In fact, it's unrepayable.

65
00:06:46,903 --> 00:06:55,394
And that's what you begin to realize, I think, when you contemplate everything that's been given to you, you know,

66
00:06:55,661 --> 00:07:23,408
from your family from your friends the good deeds and the companionship of family and friends all this is given to you and then there's things like what society gives us all our education you know our parents could not have afforded most of our parents could not have afforded to educate us and it's the same way the social services we might not have needed them up until now but if

67
00:07:23,708 --> 00:07:28,555
If we get old enough, you definitely begin to need them.

68
00:07:29,416 --> 00:07:31,178
And of course, there's our health system.

69
00:07:32,440 --> 00:07:49,547
You know, it's funny how you take something as a right and you just sort of presume that something isn't given because either you've paid for it through the national insurance or because it's taken for granted.

70
00:07:49,966 --> 00:07:54,149
But how many times have you thanked your doctors, you know, thanked the dentist?

71
00:07:54,930 --> 00:07:58,855
Now, the dentist I had here in Bishop's Castle was really good.

72
00:07:58,915 --> 00:08:09,446
The front tooth here finally gave in and he put this false tooth in, you know, and it was pretty awful.

73
00:08:09,485 --> 00:08:10,526
You've got to get used to it.

74
00:08:10,726 --> 00:08:12,208
You couldn't eat nuts.

75
00:08:12,389 --> 00:08:15,512
All the nuts got behind the tooth, behind the palate.

76
00:08:15,872 --> 00:08:18,774
So you had to take it out and wash your mouth out and stick it back in.

77
00:08:21,218 --> 00:08:27,627
And when I told him that it was a little inconvenient, he finally decided to give me a bridge.

78
00:08:27,987 --> 00:08:28,788
And there it is.

79
00:08:28,928 --> 00:08:30,531
It's absolutely fantastic.

80
00:08:31,572 --> 00:08:36,519
And it's a case of recognizing all these gifts that people have given us.

81
00:08:37,260 --> 00:08:48,136
If you bring to mind, for instance, the teachers, one or two favorite teachers that you've had, you know, it does fill the heart with a sense of gratitude.

82
00:08:49,248 --> 00:08:56,840
And finally, of course, there's nature, just the earth that we live on, which we become more and more aware of these days.

83
00:08:57,701 --> 00:09:01,847
Now, what gratitude does is it makes you want to repay.

84
00:09:02,649 --> 00:09:11,984
And because you can't repay what has been given, you can't repay something that has been given to you freely, you have to find a substitute.

85
00:09:12,644 --> 00:09:16,892
And that draws you towards just being generous ourselves.

86
00:09:17,041 --> 00:09:20,585
And that moves us into this whole area of generosity.

87
00:09:21,525 --> 00:09:25,649
Now, when the Buddha talked to lay people, he always began with generosity.

88
00:09:26,171 --> 00:09:28,874
You know, he pointed out that even a thief can be generous.

89
00:09:29,274 --> 00:09:36,302
You know, he's just taken something off you and he's very kindly given it to somebody in his family or friends.

90
00:09:37,363 --> 00:09:46,692
So when we think about generosity, the ability to give without some idea of being repaid,

91
00:09:47,871 --> 00:09:49,533
And that's quite difficult for us.

92
00:09:50,014 --> 00:09:52,337
So we have to clarify the mind about that.

93
00:09:52,979 --> 00:10:03,313
Now, there are certain times you give gifts such as Christmas, which is more like, you know, a little ritual reestablishing friendship.

94
00:10:03,333 --> 00:10:08,741
You know, so you get your pair of socks and they get their pair of socks.

95
00:10:08,942 --> 00:10:09,764
And that's fine.

96
00:10:10,445 --> 00:10:17,575
Unless, of course, the pair that they've given you is obviously much cheaper than what you spent on the socks that you gave them.

97
00:10:18,111 --> 00:10:20,815
So that's when the trouble starts.

98
00:10:21,755 --> 00:10:24,578
So there's always a bit of bargaining going on.

99
00:10:24,599 --> 00:10:28,082
It's always like a business, like in business, you see.

100
00:10:28,923 --> 00:10:45,822
So if we want to have an act of pure generosity, then you have to listen to what's going on in the background of our minds about being repaid, about being adored because of our generosity.

101
00:10:46,293 --> 00:11:08,530
So if you're going to give, for instance, a donation to a charity, and there are so many of them these days, you know, you have to sort of get yourself into that mental state where that's the only thing in your mind and heart that you are giving this in order to help somebody, right?

102
00:11:08,551 --> 00:11:10,053
And there's no hope of repayment.

103
00:11:10,073 --> 00:11:11,996
The charity is not going to give you any money back.

104
00:11:12,466 --> 00:11:15,328
So you're doing it for just that purpose.

105
00:11:15,609 --> 00:11:18,673
And when you do it for that purpose, that's when you act.

106
00:11:18,753 --> 00:11:23,158
That's when you make the donation, whether it's by card or by cash, it doesn't really matter.

107
00:11:24,219 --> 00:11:31,606
And then, of course, once you've done it, you'll hear these little voices, you know, like you are truly a very wonderful person.

108
00:11:31,626 --> 00:11:34,769
Or you might get the one of, oh, that's too much.

109
00:11:35,009 --> 00:11:36,172
What do you give so much for?

110
00:11:36,251 --> 00:11:38,254
You could have...

111
00:11:39,432 --> 00:11:42,815
So you have to be, you haven't been caught up in that, you see.

112
00:11:43,015 --> 00:11:44,957
So you've not been caught up in Mara.

113
00:11:45,197 --> 00:11:47,019
The Mara did not catch you there.

114
00:11:47,480 --> 00:11:49,341
So you can let those thoughts disappear.

115
00:11:49,682 --> 00:11:53,706
And if guilt comes, you have to point to it and say, well, that is false guilt.

116
00:11:53,927 --> 00:11:58,751
Because when I actually made the action, my heart was full of generosity.

117
00:11:59,732 --> 00:12:03,836
And the same arises when you do something for somebody.

118
00:12:04,846 --> 00:12:10,634
So I think most people, I certainly do, is say yes too quickly.

119
00:12:11,235 --> 00:12:15,120
So if somebody says, you know, I've moved into this new house.

120
00:12:15,179 --> 00:12:16,121
It's actually happened to me.

121
00:12:16,601 --> 00:12:20,989
I've moved into this new flat, you know, and we're painting it.

122
00:12:22,070 --> 00:12:25,434
You know, would you like to, you know, come and give us a hand?

123
00:12:25,815 --> 00:12:28,077
And I said, yeah, yeah, I'll come on Saturday, you see.

124
00:12:28,318 --> 00:12:31,302
And then as I'm walking away, I'm thinking, what?

125
00:12:31,602 --> 00:12:33,485
What have I given this Saturday away?

126
00:12:36,486 --> 00:12:46,083
And in that case, at that time, I was, shall we say, advanced enough to actually make myself do it, to teach myself not to say yes.

127
00:12:46,163 --> 00:12:49,549
You know, just because somebody asks something, you don't have to say yes.

128
00:12:50,150 --> 00:12:55,961
And there's a point where you can actually reflect for a moment and then, you know, say yes.

129
00:12:56,282 --> 00:12:58,125
So it's coming from a point of reflection.

130
00:12:58,184 --> 00:13:00,469
You're not done it by habit.

131
00:13:01,546 --> 00:13:15,126
So, again, that point of generosity is has to be there has to be a certain reflection about it and that you are doing it from the heart of goodwill and that you're not even expecting a thank you.

132
00:13:15,548 --> 00:13:16,629
And that's very difficult.

133
00:13:16,909 --> 00:13:22,599
You know, when I became a monastic, we're not supposed to say thank you.

134
00:13:22,619 --> 00:13:25,123
I mean, I say it in the West because people get very upset.

135
00:13:25,389 --> 00:13:28,333
But in the East, you're not supposed to, you don't say thank you.

136
00:13:28,575 --> 00:13:31,118
You see, it undermines the person's gift.

137
00:13:31,298 --> 00:13:32,440
That's the understanding.

138
00:13:33,182 --> 00:13:38,769
Because if somebody gives something to you, they don't expect you to say thank you.

139
00:13:39,750 --> 00:13:45,919
But if they expect you to say thank you and then you don't say thank you, then, of course, they feel very upset.

140
00:13:45,940 --> 00:13:48,904
And that tells you that the gift is slightly corrupted.

141
00:13:48,945 --> 00:13:50,126
They wanted praise.

142
00:13:50,167 --> 00:13:51,769
They wanted appreciation.

143
00:13:52,389 --> 00:14:05,607
So to be able to give something without that desire to be acknowledged is leading us towards a real pure heart generosity.

144
00:14:06,629 --> 00:14:13,238
And the other little telltale is just to give that little bit more that pinches.

145
00:14:14,100 --> 00:14:21,789
That little pinch is where you're truly being generous, where you're giving just that bit of extra time, just that little bit of,

146
00:14:22,090 --> 00:14:47,524
extra money and that's the point where where it just begins to hurt a little bit you know that's that's the point where you are truly extending your extending our generosity so just to recap you we have this lovely virtuous circle general this this feeling of gratitude and

147
00:14:47,908 --> 00:14:57,945
One exercise you can give yourself is just to say that tomorrow, everything, I will say thank you to everything.

148
00:14:58,024 --> 00:15:01,309
I'll say thank you to the door that opens.

149
00:15:02,110 --> 00:15:05,336
In Zen, of course, you're always gassho when you enter a room.

150
00:15:05,876 --> 00:15:08,600
You're taught to thank everything.

151
00:15:08,868 --> 00:15:11,753
You have to gassho when you approach the table.

152
00:15:12,073 --> 00:15:13,535
You gassho to the chair.

153
00:15:14,037 --> 00:15:25,517
So this whole attitude of actually not presuming on anything, not thinking that we have a right to everything, but that everything is a gift.

154
00:15:26,457 --> 00:15:30,926
And if you go through the whole day like that, you'd be surprised how it lifts you.

155
00:15:30,946 --> 00:15:32,107
It really does lift you.

156
00:15:33,808 --> 00:15:43,644
And then once you've established, once we've established more and more this sense of gratitude and the knowledge that you can't repay directly what people have given to you.

157
00:15:44,746 --> 00:15:49,575
There has to be, you have to find a way of expressing that gratitude through generosity.

158
00:15:50,375 --> 00:15:57,908
And when we are being generous, you know, just to stop for a moment and to make sure that you're doing it for pure reasons.

159
00:15:58,109 --> 00:15:58,769
That's all.

160
00:15:59,644 --> 00:16:07,234
And then to realize that when I've actually made an act of generosity with a pure heart, I've renounced something.

161
00:16:07,333 --> 00:16:09,797
I've let go of something I'm holding on to.

162
00:16:10,878 --> 00:16:14,282
And I'm actually practicing renunciation, right?

163
00:16:15,462 --> 00:16:18,066
Letting go of that grip on things.

164
00:16:18,086 --> 00:16:26,495
And that loosening of a grip, that letting go of these tight desires, wrong desires,

165
00:16:26,999 --> 00:16:46,890
is a little, every time we do that and we feel that loss of grippiness, that in a sense is a touch of divanā because one of the descriptions of divanā is that it is desireless of these sorts of wrong desires.

166
00:16:47,731 --> 00:16:52,720
So there's a lovely little practice there which, you know, is just ongoing.

167
00:16:53,222 --> 00:16:54,244
day in and day out.

168
00:16:54,303 --> 00:16:57,168
And it's only a matter of reminding ourselves to do it.

169
00:16:57,868 --> 00:17:01,393
And just very slowly, it becomes a habitude, that's all.

170
00:17:02,413 --> 00:17:06,498
And really, that's what we're doing in our practice.

171
00:17:06,598 --> 00:17:19,513
We are just changing our habits, moving away from habits which cause ourselves suffering and aren't very pleasant for others, and moving towards habits which bring us happiness.

172
00:17:20,094 --> 00:17:21,576
So there is

173
00:17:21,826 --> 00:17:25,769
you know, the gift of the practice is a natural happiness in life.

174
00:17:26,450 --> 00:17:28,952
It's not Nirvana, it's just a natural happiness.

175
00:17:29,393 --> 00:17:36,499
And this happiness that we talk about is the internal environment, you know, within ourselves.

176
00:17:37,359 --> 00:17:41,223
So this is a really powerful practice.

177
00:17:42,404 --> 00:17:45,247
And I try and remember to do it myself occasionally.

178
00:17:48,210 --> 00:17:51,292
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

179
00:17:51,678 --> 00:18:01,619
that they have not caused even greater confusion and that you will, by your practice, become liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

